                    <h2>Introduction</h2>
                    <p>Hey everyone, welcome back to my channel, Online Island! Today, we're going to dive into the world of animation. In my previous video, I showed you how to create a playlist. Now, let's create an animation.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="overview" class="mb-5">
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col">
                    <h2>Overview</h2>
                    <p>So, in this video, we'll be working on a slide show. Let's select a simple image. We'll remove the background of this image. Now, let's add an animation to this image. It's a simple process. We'll adjust the margins and make sure it fits perfectly on the screen.</p>
                    <pre><code class="bg-light p-3">
<!-- HTML example for adding an image -->
<img src="path/to/your-image.jpg" alt="Sample Image" class="animated-img">
                    </code></pre>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="devices" class="mb-5">
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col">
                    <h2>Responsiveness</h2>
                    <p>We'll also ensure that the animation looks good on different screen sizes, like mobile and tablet. We'll add a container to our image. This will help us control the animation's position.</p>
                    <pre><code class="bg-light p-3">
/* CSS example for responsiveness */
.container {
    margin: 20px;
    display: inline-block;
    position: relative;
}

@media (max-width: 768px) {
    .animated-img {
        width: 100%;
        height: auto;
    }
}
                    </code></pre>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="effects" class="mb-5">
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col">
                    <h2>Animation Effects</h2>
                    <p>Next, we'll add an animation effect. Let's try a sliding effect. We'll adjust the height and width of the animation to fit our image. We'll also adjust the timing of the animation. We want the animation to start at a specific point and end at another.</p>
                    <pre><code class="bg-light p-3">
/* CSS example for animation effects */
@keyframes slideIn {
    from {
        transform: translateX(-100%);
    }
    to {
        transform: translateX(0);
    }
}

.animated-img {
    animation: slideIn 2s ease-in-out;
}
                    </code></pre>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="instructions" class="mb-5">
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col">
                    <h2>Instructions</h2>
                    <p>[Continues with detailed instructions on adjusting animation settings, including timing, positioning, and effects.] So, guys, that's how you create a simple animation. In my next video, I'll show you how to create more complex animations.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
    </div>
